From: Ichthyostega <prg@ichthyostega.de>
Date: Sat, 29 Dec 2018 08:28:04 +0100
Subject: TrinomialPRNG - Integrate a simplified version of random_r() from
 Glibc 2.28

Start refactoring by integrating the Glibc random_r() / srandom_r() implementation

This adds yet another PRNG implementation, which incorporates a literal copy
from the Glibc 2.28 implementation, without any further simplifications.

I use Glibc 2.28 here, since it adds a simplification/clarification for the
rightshift to drop the least random bit; Since newer C++ standards require
to use an arithmetic right shift on signed values, the internal variable val
is now defined to be uint32_t, which also allows to omit the factor  & 0x7fffffff;
used in previous versinos of the Glibc.

TODO: This changeset includes a huge pile of constants and code
which can be simplified, given that our state array is known to be inline and 256 bytes large

simplify initstate_r

Observation:
 - we use 256 bytes of state and thus have TYPE_4
 - we never use setstate_r()

The library uses clever code to capture the current pointer positions of the old state,
in order to be able to restore that state later. We do not need any of that code.
In fact, we now don't use the random_state[0] anymore.

further simplify initstate_r(), srandom_r() and random_r()

Directly using the member fields of the enclosing TrinomialPRNG object greatly simplifies the code.
Moreover, the constants for the random algorithm are now completely inlined and gone
All error exits can be excluded now, and random_r() now returns its result directly.

reduce state storage

 - since we don't use the 1st storage slot in the state array
   (because we never need to restore an externally saved state),
   we can shift the whole array by one int32_t. And then we can
   turn that from an char array into an int32_t array with 32 elements.

 - then step by step unfold the struct random_data, until only the two
   active pointers remain. These can be private members of our class

completely inlined and simplified the random_r() / srandom_r() code

Basically all this inlining and rewriting should be equivalent transformations.
Hopefully I made no mistakes...

To summarise the actual changes:

 * the original code used the 1st slot in the state array to capture the pointer positions,
   in order to be able to save/restore state to an external buffer. We do not need
   this functionality. Thus I've shifted the whole state array by one, and adjusted
   its size to 63 * 4bytes long  accordingly. This should have no effect on the algorithm.

 * the original code used within srandom_r() the local variables long int lo, high.
   I consider this dangerous, since long int is the same as int on i386 (a notorious pitfall).
   Thus I change those variables to be explicitly 64bit.

optimisation: unnecessary to zero-init the state array

the init() function obviously overwrites systematically the whole content of the state array

And, as far as I can see, our code always calls init() before generating random numbers.
